          "title": "Pentecost — the harvest completed (23:15-22)",
          "body": "The Feast of Weeks (Shavuot, later called Pentecost from the Greek for 'fifty') bridges the spring and autumn feasts through a fifty-day count that spans the entire grain harvest season. The counting is itself an act of worship — 'you shall also count for yourselves' (23:15) — a daily attentiveness to time that turns the whole harvest period into a liturgical act. The feast concludes with the most elaborate offering set in the chapter: seven lambs, a bull, two rams (burnt offering), a goat (sin offering), two lambs (peace offering), and the unique wave offering of two leavened loaves (23:17-20). The leavened loaves are exceptional — the only leavened product presented to the LORD in the entire feast calendar. Their presence is best understood as representing the completed, ordinary-life harvest of the people, brought as an offering of thanks. The gleaning law appended in verse 22 reveals that the harvest thanksgiving is incomplete unless it produces tangible provision for the poor and the alien. The feast that celebrates God's agricultural provision must simultaneously become provision for the vulnerable."
