          "title": "The seventh-month cluster — Trumpets, Atonement, Booths (23:23-43)",
          "body": "The seventh month is the calendar's theological summit. Three feasts occupy it in rapid succession, each building on the previous: Trumpets opens it (1 Tishri), Atonement falls ten days in (10 Tishri), and Booths runs the final half of the month (15-22 Tishri). The Feast of Trumpets is the least-prescribed feast in the chapter — two verses, rest and a fire offering (23:24-25) — but it serves as the gathering call that inaugurates the month. The blast of the trumpet in ancient Israel signaled assembly, battle, and the approach of the King. Ten days after Trumpets, the Day of Atonement arrives as the most solemn day in the entire Israelite calendar. Three times the chapter commands 'humble your souls' (23:27, 29, 32) — the only feast in the chapter where the inner posture of the worshipper is commanded rather than the outer act of sacrifice alone. The consequence for refusing is the most severe in any feast legislation: cut off from the people (23:29) or personally destroyed by God (23:30). Atonement cannot be performatively observed; it demands genuine self-humbling. Then, five days after the Day of Atonement, Booths erupts with the chapter's concentrated notes of joy — foliage, palm branches, willows, and seven days of rejoicing before the LORD (23:40). The sequence is irreversible: atonement must precede celebration. Israel cannot rejoice in booths until her sin has been covered. The Feast of Booths then pulls the whole calendar into its memorial logic: Israel lives in temporary shelters to remember that God Himself housed her in booths in the wilderness (23:43). The feasts are thus Israel's yearly curriculum in the history of her own redemption."
