        "excerpt": "The LORD's appointed times which you shall proclaim as holy convocations — My appointed times are these.",
        "body": "The opening verses of Leviticus 23 are not administrative preamble. They are a theological declaration. The double possessive — 'the LORD's appointed times' (23:2) and 'My appointed times' (23:2) — announces before any feast is described that the calendar originates in divine ownership, not human religious creativity. Israel does not invent these festivals; she receives them. She does not choose when to celebrate; she is called. The word moed (appointed time) carries the connotation of a fixed appointment — the same word used for the Tent of Meeting (ohel moed, 'tent of appointment'), where God met with Israel. The feasts are, in a sense, portable Tents of Meeting scattered across the year.\n\nThe Sabbath (23:3) is placed before all annual feasts as the load-bearing theological premise. God does not say 'observe the Sabbath and then the feasts'; He places the Sabbath in a position that reframes everything that follows. The Sabbath — 'in all your dwellings,' not only at the sanctuary — establishes that sacred time is not limited to pilgrimage occasions but saturates every household weekly. This matters for the interpretation of the annual feasts: they are intensifications of what the weekly Sabbath already enacts. Every holy convocation is, in structure, a Sabbath — a cessation of ordinary work as an acknowledgment that God owns the time being surrendered.\n\nJohn Calvin, commenting on this passage, notes that the Sabbath's placement is pedagogical: 'God desired to show that all His appointed solemnities were, as it were, derived from the Sabbath; since they all had this in common — that they were rest from ordinary labor, a holy assembly, and a sacrifice.' (Commentaries on the Four Last Books of Moses, Vol. 2). The Sabbath is not one feast among seven; it is the grammar in which all the feasts are written.\n\nThe summary statement of verse 4 — 'These are the appointed times of the LORD, holy convocations which you shall proclaim at the times appointed for them' — functions as a title for what follows. The word 'proclaim' (qara) is significant: Israel does not merely observe the feasts privately; she announces them. The holy convocation is a public summons, a communal act, an event that requires the assembly of the local church in its ancient form.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Moed* (appointed time) shares its root with *ohel moed* (Tent of Meeting/Appointment) — the feasts are, in effect, moveable Tents of Meeting distributed across the sacred year. *Miqra qodesh* (holy convocation) — *miqra* from *qara*, to call or proclaim; a called-assembly, not a self-assembled gathering. *Shabbat shabbaton* (23:3) — the doubled form is intensive: 'a Sabbath of sabbaths,' the most complete cessation."
