        "title": "Passover, Unleavened Bread, and Firstfruits — redemption, separation, and the firstborn of the harvest",
        "range": "23:5-14",
        "excerpt": "In the first month, on the fourteenth day of the month at twilight is the LORD's Passover.",
        "body": "The spring feasts constitute Israel's foundational rehearsal of her own origin. Passover (14 Nisan) anchors the entire calendar in the historical event of Exodus 12 — the night the lamb's blood on the doorposts caused the destroying angel to pass over Israel's firstborn. The precision of 'the fourteenth day of the month at twilight' (23:5) is not calendar pedantry; it binds the annual feast to the actual historical night. Christianity is not a religion of timeless spiritual principles; it is a religion of specific events. The Passover feast keeps that specificity alive year by year.\n\nUnleavened Bread (15-21 Nisan) runs immediately from Passover, creating a connected eight-day event in practice. Leaven in Scripture consistently signifies that which corrupts and permeates — the moral residue of Egypt, the influence of the old life (cf. 1 Corinthians 5:6-8; Matthew 16:6, 11-12). Seven days without leaven enacts the completeness of the break with Egypt. Israel does not depart gradually; the feast enacts total separation. The requirement that no laborious work be done on the first and seventh days (23:7-8) bookends the feast with holy convocations, framing the week as liturgically suspended between two assemblies.\n\nFirstfruits introduces the harvest theology that will run through Pentecost. 'When you enter the land... and reap its harvest, then you shall bring in the sheaf of the first fruits of your harvest to the priest' (23:10). The conditional 'when you enter the land' is significant: this feast cannot be observed in the wilderness. It awaits the fulfillment of the land promise. The wave-sheaf offering — elevated before the LORD before any crop is consumed (23:14) — enacts the principle that the harvest is God's before it is Israel's. Every bite of the new crop is preceded by an acknowledgment of divine ownership.\n\nThe apostle Paul identifies the risen Christ as the antitype of this wave-sheaf: 'Christ has been raised from the dead, the first fruits of those who are asleep' (1 Corinthians 15:20). The wave-sheaf points to the resurrection — the first ripened grain of the final harvest of the dead. And the timing is precise: Christ rose 'on the day after the Sabbath' following Passover weekend, the exact day prescribed for the wave-sheaf (23:11). The shadow and the substance share not only their theological content but their date.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pesach* — from *pasach*, to pass over, to spare; the LXX renders it *pascha*, the term the NT uses for both the Jewish feast and Christ's atonement (1 Cor 5:7: *to pascha hēmōn etuthē Christos*). *Matstsah* (unleavened bread) — the absence of leaven marks the food of liberation: eaten in haste (Ex 12:11), in separation from Egypt's fermented culture. *Reshit* (first fruits, 23:10) — beginning, choicest; the word used for wisdom in Proverbs 8:22 and creation in Genesis 1:1."
