        "excerpt": "You shall count fifty days to the day after the seventh sabbath; then you shall present a new grain offering to the LORD.",
        "body": "The fifty-day count from Firstfruits to the Feast of Weeks (Shavuot) is the most time-intensive exercise in the chapter. Israel is commanded to count — 'you shall also count for yourselves' (23:15) — seven complete sabbaths plus one day, totaling fifty days. The Greek word for fifty (pentēkonta) gives the feast its New Testament name: Pentecost. The counting itself is a liturgical act: each day of the harvest is numbered before God, turning the entire agricultural season into a sustained act of attentiveness to divine provision.\n\nThe Feast of Weeks celebrates the completion of the grain harvest with the most elaborate offering set in the chapter. Seven lambs, a bull, two rams (burnt offering), a goat (sin offering), two lambs (peace offerings), and the distinctive wave offering of two leavened loaves (23:17-20). The leavened loaves are exegetically significant: leaven is forbidden from all offerings to the altar (Leviticus 2:11), yet here two leavened loaves are waved before the LORD. Their presence is not a liturgical exception to be explained away but a deliberate theological statement: the completed harvest of ordinary, leaven-pervaded human life is brought to God as it is. The wave offering of leavened bread alongside the sin and peace offerings suggests the whole of human life — including its imperfection — presented in worship, covered by the sin offering, restored to fellowship by the peace offering.\n\nThe gleaning law of verse 22 is the chapter's most surprising structural feature: inserted between Pentecost and Trumpets, it interrupts the feast calendar with a neighbor-ethics law. The interruption is the point. Howard Hendricks often pressed students to ask: 'Why is this here?' The answer is that the harvest celebration is incomplete if the worshipper leaves the corner of the field bare on the way to the sanctuary. Authentic worship of the God who gives harvest must generate provision for those who receive no harvest. The feasts are not spiritually self-contained; they produce ethics.\n\nThe New Testament reads Pentecost as the fulfillment of the Feast of Weeks: the Holy Spirit was poured out on the assembled disciples on the very day of Shavuot (Acts 2:1-4). The fifty-day interval from Christ's resurrection (Firstfruits) to Pentecost maps precisely onto the fifty-day Omer count of Leviticus 23. The 'new grain offering to the LORD' (23:16) finds its antitype in the new community of the Spirit — the firstfruits of the new creation harvest — gathered in Jerusalem, speaking in every tongue.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chamishshim yom* — fifty days; the Greek *pentēkonta* gives Pentecost its NT name (Acts 2:1, *en tē hēmera tēs pentēkostēs*). *Chamets* (leaven, 23:17) — the only leavened offering waved before the LORD in the feast calendar; the two loaves are often read typologically as representing redeemed humanity (Jew and Gentile) brought to God complete with their histories. *Leqet* (gleaning, 23:22) — the leftovers of the reaped grain, assigned by divine command to the poor; the same word used in Ruth 2:2-3, where Ruth gleans in Boaz's field under this very provision."
